answers.body_markdown:
 1.  For `List&lt;Car&gt; vehicles = new ArrayList&lt;Car&gt;();` you could use simple the diamond operator like this `new ArrayList&lt;&gt;();`
 2. Your `List&lt;? super BMW280&gt; bmws` means that you will have a list of BMW280 or any typ more specific than BMW280, what means subtypes of BMW280 like `public class BMW290 extends BMW280`. 

If you are only pulling items from a generic collection, it is a producer and you should use extends; if you are only stuffing items in, it is a consumer and you should use super. From the name
    of your list I assume that you intended to list all kind of BMWs.
    You could do this instead: 

        public static void main(String[] args) {
            List&lt;Car&gt; vehicles = new ArrayList&lt;&gt;();
            vehicles.add(new BMW());
            vehicles.add(new BMW240());
            //&lt;? super BMW&gt; if you want to add also new BMW() 
            List&lt;? super BMW240&gt; bmws = vehicles;
            bmws.add(new BMW240());
            bmws.add(new BMW280());
        }

